{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2b55f1a7-4130-4cfd-840b-e045b4bf509e","content":"**No, you no longer need `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` on .NET 10 SDK.**\n\nIn .NET 10, `dotnet test` uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively by default — the property was only needed in .NET 9 to opt in. You can safely remove it:\n\n```xml\n<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>  <!-- remove this -->\n```\n\nYour project already has `EnableMSTestRunner` set, which is still required to build the test project as an MTP executable. Everything else is wired up automatically by the SDK.\n\nWant me to remove the redundant property from your `.csproj`?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"415a0438-7bf2-4f25-a9ad-24ff761ca065","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is on .NET 10 SDK (10.0.100) and wants to know about Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) support in `dotnet test`.\n\nIn .NET 10, `dotnet test` has native MTP support built-in. The key change is:\n\n1. Starting with .NET 10 SDK, `dotnet test` uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively (it's the default test runner integration).\n2. The `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property is **no longer needed** in .NET 10 — it was required in .NET 9 to opt-in to the MTP-based `dotnet test` experience, but in .NET 10 it's the default behavior.\n\n\n3. They can safely remove `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` from their project file since it's now redundant, though it's still recognized for backward compatibility. However, they'll still need `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` if they want to use the MSTest runner, which compiles the test project as an executable with MTP.","outputTokens":463,"requestId":"BC2E:5FB6B:1C45FC3:1F5E723:69FA9122"},"id":"ffef357f-a982-4a5c-8200-152776846344","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:54:05.255Z","parentId":"f0115476-410e-4276-9008-986fad9d8cc2"}
